social_posts.post_text: The @authenticasheville LGBTQIA2S+ and BIPOC Creator Grant closes in roughly three weeks! It is open to folks who live in the United States and who identify with one or both groups. You do not have to identify with both groups in order to be considered. @carolineperdue and I are both self-taught when it comes to photography and videos and we recognize that there are many barriers for people who are trying to get started or continue their journey in a creative field, whether it’s writing, painting, woodworking, dance, spoken word, sculpture, etc and so we’re aiming to help someone get where they’re trying to go in our own small way via this grant. We’ve been pumped about the responses we’ve received so far. Please feel free to share this with someone you think might be a great fit. The application closes at 11:59 pm EST on January 7, 2023. Link in bio to apply. ✨

@authenticasheville has a LGBTQIA2S+BIPOC Creator Grant available. Applications are accepted until tomorrow, Saturday, January 7 (end of day). This grant is open to anyone who lives in the US and identifies with either or both communities. We want to help another creative on their journey, so please apply and share with anyone you think is interested. Link in bio to apply.

I've been learning about my avoidant attachment style and how to have a secure one due to the gentle suggestion from @e.mcgrady to follow Julie Mennanos @thesecurerelationship. If you have any interest in learning more about yourself and how you relate to other people, this account really teaches the subject in a way that's easy to understand and APPLY. 
The most helpful thing ive learned so far is how to be a more careful listener which has led to less conflict that feels BAD, yucky, stuck. 
For all the toxic ways social media can influence my life, having these tools show up in my feed every day has been so helpful.
Photo: @e.mcgrady

Watched a movie last night where a donkey, horse and cow were allowed inside. 
A friend told me earlier in the week that shes extending the fenced in area for her two donkeys so they can visit her at the kitchen door. 
I had dogs growing up and also mostly since being  all grown up. But the last 4 years or so we have been pet free and the freedom has been amazing. That being said, we've had Maggie for only a few months and I can't imagine life without her. Animals help make humans better, for sure.
Seeing how other people create their home space gives me such joy. This patio felt like a hug to me.
Feeling my heart in a tussle today by having to set another repeated boundary thats its not enough to love me while not loving or including my marriage because she is a she. Ooof.
This little raccoon hung the moon.
You and me and Maggie 🐶 make three and that’s more than enough to be family 🌈
Feeling so grateful to be spending time with my brother and his incredible family.

Wowee Maui. This is a snorkeling beach accessed thru private land that allowed visitors to respectfully walk thru while staying on the path. The trail passed unmarked graves buried beneath towering trees- a rainforest nestled between the road and the ocean.

[TW: racism, white supremacy] I've been making my way through Michelle Alexander's The New Jim Crow. Its a massive education. The War on Drugs started when I was just a few years old. However, White Supremacy, my privilege and my whiteness, shielded me from seeing the truth behind the War on Drugs, which is the mass incarceration of Black (and Brown) people primarily for drug offenses for which white people are let go. Once released from prison or accepting a plea deal they often reenter society with a felony conviction which is a life sentence to discrimination and disenfranchisement.

I was born and raised in Baton Rouge, Louisiana, home of Angola Prison (only an hour away.) Growing up, Angola Prison was a place that was mentioned in conversation but I didn't grasp even the tip of the iceberg as to what it actually stood for: the removal and dehumanization and locking up of Black people. Angola was the name of the plantation, located previously at the same site, owned by a slave trader and also Angola is the name of the country in West Africa where human beings were stolen from and sold into enslavement. Angola Prison is the largest prison in the US. The Black population in Louisiana is 33%. The Black population at Angola is currently 64%. I've known about Angola Prison for my entire life and yet I was ignorant of the true horror of Angola Prison. This is what White Supremacy wants. 
Currently over in Tennessee, two Black Democratic State Representatives were expelled from their positions (but not the white woman who stood with them) for peacefully protesting and standing for Gun Safety Laws. This is another example of White Supremacy. 
It's embarrassing, humiliating, and shameful to learn our history AND it will keep happening as long as we stay complicit by way of ignorance and a lack of investment to learn, which will surely lead us to change. The dismemberment of White Supremacy requires the white population to care, to learn, to look, and to DO. At almost 45 years old, I am showing up late. If anybody else is on a similar journey, I'm open to listening and sharing more about it and learning how we can be better allies and co-conspirators.

The dark curtain religious extremists and right wing politicians are trying to pull over us in the LGBTQIA2+ community feels like it’s coming from all sides. In Ohio, there have been three different Nazi groups in the last few weeks attacking gatherings for Drag shows. You might think that the Republican politicians that have been trying to pass more bills targeting the rights of Trans people in their state would be a bit uncomfortable with the public display of swastikas co mingling with anti-Trans support, but it’s not. They are continuing with hearings to target Trans people. There are even evangelical leaders from this country (Arizona specifically) with Family Watch International traveling to Uganda to influence Afrian governments there with the passage of the Anti-Homosexuality Act, formerly known as the Kill The Gays Bill. This bill is intended to make homosexuality illegal and punishable by death.

The violence we are facing is increasing and I feel scared. I have dealt with losing the majority of my family because of being gay and not having their support, but it never made me feel scared for my safety and my human rights like I am feeling these days. 

Thank you Minnesota and Washington for passing laws protecting the Trans community! 

Friday night at Pack Square in Asheville, NC from 5-6:30 pm Campaign for Southern Equality, Youth Outright, and Blue Ridge Pride are hosting a rally to support Trans Youth in NC! Hope to see you there!

Love is love is love.

A handful of years ago my relationship with my parents and my sister went thru a steep decline because I told them I could no longer compartmentalize my primary relationship from my relationships with them. They want it to be enough for me (and my wife) that they only see her as my best friend. Or they see her as my life partner in a civil union. Or that she is my wife to me, but to them she isn't and what's the big deal? I had been accepting 'Christian' versions like this for 20 years and I'd had enough. There is so much damage caused by being denied rights, especially when it's projected from a religious lens. The burden I feel from being excluded from my own immediate family never leaves me. 
Celebrating Pride month used to bring me only joy but now it brings me dread. I feel even further under attack during this month than the rest of the year and protesting all of these anti-LGBT during Pride month feels terrible but it's our current climate. If you are looking for ways to support visit @humanrightscampaign @southernequality @trevorproject @blueridgepride @equalitync @cornbread.roses

YOU CAN’T BAN QUEER JOY! Queer People are here, we always have been and always will be. To all my LGBTQIA2S friends, I see you and I love you and I mean it. This life is hard, real hard, and there are days when I just want to quit but we are not alone and the times when we get to share space together and make memories are among the greatest joys in my life. We all deserve to love who we love, without fear, without shame, without consequence. And until that day arrives, we go to work. And as I’m learning, sometimes that means rest and sometimes that means unapologetic joy; where the hate and intolerance just can’t get in. Today it means JOY. To my friends and family who have committed to allyship and being co-conspirators, I see you too, and am so grateful for you. I may never know about the times you stood up for us, donated money, protested, had a tough conversation, wrote, called, created or offered brave or safe space but I appreciate it all the same. We’re in the fight for our lives these days, literally. You know the stats by now. And to know that you’ve got our backs mean more than you could possibly know. Together we make this world safer, better, more loving, more caring, more humane. Once more for those just waking up to what this life is all about: it’s LOVE, it’s LOVE, it’s LOVE. 🏳️‍🌈🏳️‍⚧️🏳️‍🌈🏳️‍⚧️

I've been feeling really inspired recently by older people. Like nearly twice my age and I'm 45. I think what's most impactful is seeing the joy they experience by being able to do physical things they still love. It doesn't seem to matter that they may be much slower or maybe they can't do it for as long. It's the 'doing' itself that seems to bring joy.

One tow truck, Uber ride, hotel room, U-haul van and a scratched cornea later and we are all home safe and sound. What an intense 24 hours! Thanks for all the kind messages. We are home and safe and wow a cold beer never tasted so good lol. Not sure when we’ll get our van back…apparently it needs an entirely new engine. One things for sure though, I’m glad I have these two by my side. Pretty sure if it was me alone I’d still be in the side of the road in one big messy meltdown of a puddle. Love you @carolineperdue and little Maggie 🐶

Closing out the week with good news! @carolineperdue and I both earned our FAA Remote Pilot Certificate by passing the exam so we are now officially able to fly our drone for commercial work which means we’ll be able to offer our clients hi-res still photos and 4K video. As of 2022 only 7.9% of all certified drone pilots were women so we’re psyched to take up our place in the sky!

I've got a neighbor that mows her lawn and I'd guess she's in her late 80s. My other neighbor still mows her half acre of a hill and she's 71. 
I ran up the mountain in our neighborhood this morning and pictured Erin running next to me on the incline cause she's a little goat and had the idea to run this mountain, once a month, over a year ago.
I leaned on all their strength to pull me up and it sure was pretty once I got to the top and could see all the layers thru the rain and fog.

Celebrating 7 years of being in business over here! Thanks to everyone who’s supported @authenticasheville. We both made drastic changes to our work lives in order to try and do a dream of taking photos full-time. Since then we’ve expanded to video (including drone work!) and writing but the vision is still the same: to share stories that need to be told and to do so through an intersectional point of view. We’re aiming to increase representation on both sides of the lens. We’re here to take up space and to help create room for others. It was scary, sometimes still is, but we are committed to what we’re doing and are grateful to you all for caring, sharing, showing up, holding space, learning and unlearning with us, empathizing, and adding your own joy to our wins. Thanks again for all the ways y’all have showed up for us, whether it’s been via hiring us for a project, supporting work we’ve made (especially the branded work), your encouragement, a share in your stories, a text to let us know you’re thinking of us, coming to an event, mentioning our names in a room we’re not in, and most of all, just plain, real, honest to good friendship. We see you and we are so appreciative of you.
Home sunsets

It’s been a week! Mountains to sea and back again. Maggie has had a bunch of short, practice road trips to get her used to van life and seems to be loving the ever changing scenery and smells. C and I have fallen into our usual travel rhythm. There’s an ease to our division of labor and ability to navigate a small space with shoulder taps and grunts. At times it’s felt as if we’d never stopped doing this back when the world shut down. But my body knows differently having become accustomed to the creature comforts that is hot running water and my bed. Still, it’s more than worth it. We saw the sun rise today from a pull off while sipping coffee and flying the drone, bodies sore from two amazing hikes and one run yesterday. Little Maggie hates the drone but we’re working on that. We’re headed north into the Catskills today. Please let us know if you have any recommendations on BIPOC and LGBTQ-owned spots in the area! 🚐

Today is the turnaround point of our work trip around the northeast at what we hoped was the peak of fall color. It's been so very beautiful and being able to be outside for the majority of each day helps me feel ready for the impending winter.

🍁 Fall in the Blue Ridge Mountains has been incredible so far and the best is yet to come. 

🍁 This coming week, Oct 22-28 should be amazing for seeing fall color. The Blue Ridge Parkway is gonna be a great and if we had to pick one hike to spotlight right now it’d be Moore Cove Falls. 

🍁 Check back this week and next for more fall color updates.

We took our adventure pup Maggie to a ‘new to her’ beach yesterday and she loved it so much she peed about every ten feet around the campground.
When we got back home yesterday she was so excited, she retrieved six toys out of her toy box one by one and thrashed around with them on the couch. 
Sometimes I really do wish I was a dog.

Before there was ever a business or an Instagram there were photos, most of which never got printed. There were countless stories that were never shared and memories that just live in me and @carolineperdue’s heads. In backing up the last quarters work, I went down memory lane and found a handful of my favorites. Most of them were taken between 2016 and 2018 or before, when we were just starting out. Looking at them, I can still feel some of the feelings I felt in the moment. Photos are good like that; videos arguably better. And in looking at them it feels important to acknowledge and give thanks, literally to you if you’re reading this, and everyone else who’s been cheering us on, supporting our work, showing up, and overall just being there for us. It’s meant more than you could know and we feel it even more deeply during the holidays, which, for every joyous moment can often have an accompanying pang of hard. Love y’all, thanks for being here.

Sitting outside in the sun at the dealership waiting for our van that is just having routine maintenance and two people have come outside to let me know there are chairs available inside. One of them even offered to bring a chair outside for me, hot coffee, and snacks. They can’t seem to understand why I would choose to be outside in the sunshine. Five ⭐️ for customer service today.
When your dog is sleeping next to you while you are working and they take a big deep breath and sink even deeper into their nap does it create a moment of awareness that helps you relax as well?

I half read an article in the New York Times about dog culture and the politics of how you train your dog. We have a dog that has the shrillest and most punctuating bark I’ve ever heard and she loves to use her voice when she is hungry, excited, thinks we might leave the house without her, etc. It’s been puzzling to figure out how to reward when she’s quiet in an effort stop her barking or coach/teach her to stop mid-bark. But right now, as I look over at her swaddled in a hand knit blanket like a small child and deep sleeping on the couch, I see the proof that she really owns us completely and if her ear crushing barking never stops we will still adorn her kibble with green beans, pumpkin, and gently squished blueberries. Love you Maggie.
